  <!-- Section: Common Mistakes -->
  <section id="mistakes" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Common Mistakes to Avoid</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Expecting US Visa-Free Travel</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Dominica passport does NOT provide US visa-free access. You still need US visa or ESTA (which can be denied). If US access is important, consider Grenada instead—it has E-2 treaty with US allowing investor visa applications after citizenship.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Inadequate Source of Funds Documentation</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Bank statements alone aren't enough. You must prove legitimate origin: business records, employment contracts, tax returns, inheritance documents, property sale contracts. Vague explanations cause delays or rejection. Prepare comprehensive evidence.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Choosing Real Estate for Wrong Reasons</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Real estate costs $100,000 more than EDF with limited liquidity. Dominica is tiny with minimal real estate market. Unless you genuinely want Caribbean vacation property, EDF is better value. Don't choose real estate just because "it's an asset."</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Using Unlicensed Agents</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Only licensed agents can submit applications. "Facilitators" offering discounts often cause problems or disappear with funds. Verify agent license on official Dominica CBI website. Licensed agents display their authorization number.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="border-l-4 border-red-500 pl-4">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900">Planning to Actually Live There</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">Dominica is beautiful but undeveloped. Population 75,000, one small hospital, limited infrastructure. If you plan to actually reside (vs. just holding passport), research carefully. Most CBI holders never visit—they use the passport for travel while living elsewhere.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Healthcare in Dominica -->
