  <!-- Section: FAQ -->
  <section id="faq" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is Dominica CBI legitimate?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Yes. Dominica's program has operated since 1993 with government oversight and international due diligence standards. It's recognized by the Caribbean Community (CARICOM) and maintains visa-free agreements with 145 countries. The program funds national development—hurricane recovery, housing, infrastructure.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Why is Dominica cheaper than St. Kitts?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Market positioning and demand. St. Kitts commands premium for "Platinum Standard" brand, oldest program status, and fastest processing. Dominica positions on value—similar travel benefits at lower cost. Both are legitimate; choice depends on budget vs. brand preference.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get US visa-free with Dominica passport?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. Dominica passport requires US visa or ESTA for travel to the United States. If US access matters, consider Grenada—its E-2 treaty allows investors to apply for US E-2 visa after obtaining citizenship. Dominica is best for those focused on UK/EU travel.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to visit Dominica?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          No. The entire process is done remotely through your agent. You never need to visit—not for application, not for passport collection (can be shipped), and not to maintain citizenship. No physical presence requirement whatsoever. Most citizens never visit the island.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What happens if application is rejected?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          If rejected, you may receive partial refund of EDF contribution (minus due diligence and processing fees already paid). Rejection is typically due to failed due diligence—criminal history, sanctions, or undisclosed issues. Approval rate for well-prepared applications with clean backgrounds is high (~95%+).
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-neutral-50 rounded-lg p-6">
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How long does the passport last?</h3>
        <p class="text-neutral-600">
          Dominica passports are valid for 10 years and renewable for life. Citizenship itself is permanent and inheritable—children born to citizens are also citizens. Renewal requires minimal documentation and standard passport fee (~$200). Can be done through agents or embassy.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Section: Final Verdict -->
  <section id="verdict" class="scroll-mt-24 mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

    <p class="mb-4">
      Dominica offers the world's most affordable legitimate citizenship by investment at $100,000. The "Nature Isle" provides visa-free access to 145 countries including UK, EU Schengen, and Singapore—all major destinations except the US. For budget-conscious applicants, the value is unmatched.
